  "prompt": "How Indian Air Force Chief SP Tyagi was involved in Augusta Westland Scam?",
  "response": "Chief Marshal Shashindra Pal Tyagi, also known as SP Tyagi, was accused of corruption in the AugustaWestland VVIP helicopter deal, which involved the purchase of 12 helicopters intended for use by top Indian government officials. The scam came to light when it was alleged that kickbacks were paid to Indian officials to secure the contract for AugustaWestland, a subsidiary of Finmeccanica, now known as Leonardo.\n\nThe accusations against SP Tyagi primarily centered around his alleged role in influencing the procurement process to favor AugustaWestland. It was claimed that he, along with his cousins and other officials, received bribes to ensure that AugustaWestland met the technical specifications and operational requirements set by the Indian Air Force, which were reportedly tailored to favor the company's bid.\n\nInvestigations revealed that changes to the operational ceiling of the helicopters were made, which ostensibly opened the door for AugustaWestland to qualify for the contract. These changes allegedly occurred during Tyagi's tenure as the Air Force Chief, and it was suggested that he had a hand in recommending and approving these modifications.\n\nIn 2012, the Italian authorities arrested Giuseppe Orsi, CEO of Finmeccanica, making the corruption allegations public. Subsequently, Indian investigative agencies, including the Central Bureau of Investigation (CBI) and the Enforcement Directorate (ED), initiated probes into the matter. SP Tyagi was arrested in December 2016 by the CBI along with several others in connection with the scam.\n\nThe AugustaWestland scam garnered significant attention due to the high-profile nature of the individuals involved and the substantial financial implications, which included suspected kickbacks amounting to millions of dollars. Tyagi's arrest was seen as a significant development in the ongoing efforts to address corruption within India's defense procurement processes.",
